When I was in high school, I patiently waited for the year Physics came along.  We got to the chapter that had a picture of a planet in a droopy grid(you know, explaining gravitational effects on time and space) and I had always wanted to know more about that.  I got tired of hearing all this stuff in scifi and not knowing what it really is.  I took him aside and asked him to explain.  His answer:
&quot;I don&#39;t really know anything about astrophysics.&quot;
*head-&gt;desk*

&quot;Why learn this when I can just become a reality star!? 
I&#39;d rather find out which 16 year-old is pregnant on MTV than learn about quantum theory&quot; 
~ More than half the people I went to high school with

I&#39;ve been working with 4th and 5th grade science classes for about a year.  I&#39;ve actually heard arguments like this many times for every subject.  Every expert in a field says &quot;If we want to be competitive kids need to learn more about my field!&quot; 

And they are right.

The problem is that there simply isn&#39;t enough time to teach kids everything they need to know.  Any argument about what we should spend more time teaching needs to include what we need to spend less time teaching.

Silent Weapons for Quiet Wars

